You'll find tutorials on everything from basic stitches like single crochet (sc) and double crochet (dc) to more complex techniques. Additionally, the blog features articles on various crochet projects and pattern roundups like blankets, afghans, doilies, shawls, hats, mittens, amigurumi, and motifs. With so many crochet patterns and tutorials, you'll never run out of projects to try.   We believe in community, which is why we encourage our readers to share their projects and experiences. We also welcome questions and suggestions for our content. Follow us on social media, including Instagram, to connect with us and other crocheters. We’re dedicated to sharing our love for crochet and hope you’ll join us. So whether you're a beginner or an experienced crocheter, check out Crochet Penguin for all your crochet needs!

Full Description: Developed at Stanford, our patented Xirtam3 technology is a hybrid-hydrogel consisting of a self-assembling peptide EFK8 and Poloxamer 407. In a published study1 it was shown that when combined, the constituent parts form a highly desirable nanofiber network creating a 3-dimensional structure that resembles the extracellular matrix our own bodies create to heal tissue, otherwise known as a “scaffold”.  The Xirtam3  technology anchors to viable tissue and forms a bridge for cells to translocate into the scaffold structure, designed for cell attachment and cell dispersion throughout the network, allowing cells and tissue to regenerate more effectively. Our technology can be applied in the fields of aesthetic dermatology, wound care, stem cell research, tissue engineering and more.

Description: Save time and money by preventing, finding, and fixing IoT vulnerabilities before they cause harm.
Full Description: Internet-of-things (IoT) devices are rapidly growing in number and impact. These devices affect all aspects of life from our homes to the stability of our power grid and medical systems. Though the proliferation of IoT creates new opportunities, it also creates new targets and introduces risks for consumers and businesses. In particular, devices which previously had small footprints and limited capabilities now have broad attack surfaces; vulnerabilities in them may impact human trust, safety, and security. Current methods to secure embedded devices are complex and ineffective. Both the makers and purchasers of devices must have verifiable information to trust their security. Pilot Security automates this process, uncovering security vulnerabilities about all aspects of IoT device operations. The technology uses advanced automated analytic techniques we developed over years of manual cybersecurity reverse engineering combined with large public vulnerability databases to identify the most pressing security issues, inform the user, and provide actionable recommendations on remediation.
